,"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman presents with a two-day history of right flank pain that comes and goes in intensity, associated with chills, fever and dysuria. On examination she looks unwell with a temperature of 38.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, blood pressure 120/90 mmHg and pulse 100/min. She is exquisitely tender to palpation in the right loin and moderately tender in the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute appendicitis","Acute cholecystitis","Acute pyelonephritis","Renal calculus","Pancreatitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a picture of ascending urinary infection leading to \u003Cstrong\u003Epyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E. This is primarily suggested by the site of the pain, its colicky nature, as well as the dysuria. The fever and dysuria indicate an infected renal system, whereas the presentation of pain alone would be more in keeping with a renal calculus (renal colic). Furthermore, renal angle tenderness by itself would be unlikely in uncomplicated renal calculus disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute appendicitis is commonly generalised pain localising to the right iliac fossa later in the disease course. A pelvic appendix may cause urinary frequency from irritation of the bladder, but it will not cause dysuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute cholecystitis can present with similarly proceeding variable pain (which becomes constant), however, the pain will be located in the right upper quadrant and this area will generally be very tender on palpation. Further there is no background history of biliary colic or gallstones, reducing the likelihood of this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPancreatitis patients can present severely unwell with deranged vital signs and generalised abdominal pain. However, classically this would radiate to the back and the patient would have intractable nausea + vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Flank pain and renal angle tenderness equates to an ascending urinary infection, until proven otherwise."],"references":["Lee YJ, Cho S, Kim SR. Unilateral and bilateral acute pyelonephritis: differences in clinical presentation, progress and outcome. Postgraduate medical journal. 2014; 90(1060): 80-85."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74889"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1087"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74889"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:26:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:26:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1087"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"